<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="561" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,657,1187]" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1053,1079]" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">Remarks</emphasis>
. Although only known from the female, we feel justified in describing this species as new as it differs from all other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1916" box="[433,561,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[433,561,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">Daimachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a short almost parallel sided crown and also it is the largest species known in the genus. However, its placement in the genus is tentative due to the unavailability of male specimens and it may represent a genus different from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1916" box="[642,770,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[642,770,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">Daimachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
